# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asyncio-python
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] In computer programming, the **async/await pattern** is a syntactic feature of many programming languages that allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] The feature is found in C#, C++, Python, F#, Hack, Julia, Dart, Kotlin, Rust, Nim, JavaScript, and Swift.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] F# added asynchronous workflows with await points in version 2.0 in 2007.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] This influenced the async/await mechanism added to C#.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Haskell lead developer Simon Marlow created the async package in 2010.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Microsoft first released a version of C# with async/await in the Async CTP (2011).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] It was later officially released in C# 5 (2012).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Python added support for async/await with version 3.5 in 2015 adding 2 new keywords, `async` and `await`.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] TypeScript added support for async/await with version 1.7 in 2015.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] JavaScript added support for async/await in 2017 as part of ECMAScript 2017 JavaScript edition.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Rust added support for async/await with version 1.39.0 in 2019 using the `async` keyword and the `.await` postfix operator, both introduced in the 2018 edition of the language.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] C++ added support for async/await with version 20 in 2020 with 3 new keywords `co_return`, `co_await`, `co_yield`.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Swift added support for async/await with version 5.5 in 2021, adding 2 new keywords `async` and `await`.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] This was released alongside a concrete implementation of the Actor model with the `actor` keyword which uses async/await to mediate access to each actor from outside.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] A function using async/await can use as many `await` expressions as it wants, and each will be handled in the same way (though a promise will only be returned to the caller for the first await, while every other await will utilize internal callbacks).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] A function can also hold a promise object directly and do other processing first (including starting other asynchronous tasks), delaying awaiting the promise until its result is needed.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Functions with promises also have promise aggregation methods that allow the program to await multiple promises at once or in some special pattern (such as C#'s `Task.WhenAll()`, which returns a valueless `Task` that resolves when all of the tasks in the arguments have resolved).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Many promise types also have additional features beyond what the async/await pattern normally uses, such as being able to set up more than one result callback or inspect the progress of an especially long-running task.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] In the particular case of C#, and in many other languages with this language feature, the async/await pattern is not a core part of the language's runtime, but is instead implemented with lambdas or continuations at compile time.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Because of this, if an interface method needs to return a promise object, but itself does not require `await` in the body to wait on any asynchronous tasks, it does not need the `async` modifier either and can instead return a promise object directly.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] For instance, a function might be able to provide a promise that immediately resolves to some result value (such as C#'s `Task.FromResult()`), or it may simply return another method's promise that happens to be the exact promise needed (such as when deferring to an overload).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] One important caveat of this functionality, however, is that while the code resembles traditional blocking code, the code is actually non-blocking and potentially multithreaded, meaning that many intervening events may occur while waiting for the promise targeted by an `await` to resolve.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] The C language does not support await/async.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Some coroutine libraries such as *s_task* simulate the keywords await/async with macros.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] In C++, await (named `co_await` in C++ to emphasise its context in coroutines) has been officially merged into C++20.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Support for it, coroutines, and the keywords such as `co_await` are available in GCC and MSVC compilers while Clang has partial support.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] To call it, use `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] It is worth noting that `std::promise` and `std::future`, although it would seem that they would be awaitable objects, implement none of the machinery required to be returned from coroutines and be awaited using `co_await`.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Programmers must implement a number of public member functions, such as `await_ready`, `await_suspend`, and `await_resume` on the return type in order for the type to be awaited on.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] In 2012, C# added the async/await pattern in C# with version 5.0, which Microsoft refers to as the task-based asynchronous pattern (TAP).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Async methods usually return either `void`, `Task`, `Task<T>`, `ValueTask` or `ValueTask<T>`.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] User code can define custom types that async methods can return through custom *async method builders* but this is an advanced and rare scenario.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Async methods that return `void` are intended for event handlers; in most cases where a synchronous method would return `void`, returning `Task` instead is recommended, as it allows for more intuitive exception handling (note that `Task<void>` is invalid in C#).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Methods that make use of `await` must be declared with the `async` keyword.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] In methods that have a return value of type `Task<T>`, methods declared with `async` must have a return statement of type assignable to `T` instead of `Task<T>`; the compiler wraps the value in the `Task<T>` generic.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] It is also possible to `await` methods that have a return type of `Task` or `Task<T>` that are declared without `async`.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] The following async method downloads data from a URL using `await`.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Because this method issues a task for each URI before requiring completion with the `await` keyword, the resources can load at the same time instead of waiting for the last resource to finish before starting to load the next.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] In 2007, F# added asynchronous workflows with version 2.0.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] The asynchronous workflows are implemented as CE (computation expressions).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] They can be defined without specifying any special context (like `async` in C#).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] F# asynchronous workflows append a bang (!) to keywords to start asynchronous tasks.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Java does not have `async` and `await` keywords in the language, however it can be emulated using the `java.util.concurrent` package, such as the class `CompletableFuture` (introduced in Java 8).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Asynchronous programming is later improved in Java 21 with the introduction of virtual threads and structured task scopes.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] The await operator in JavaScript (and TypeScript) can only be used from inside an async function or at the top level of a module.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] If the parameter is a promise, execution of the async function will resume when the promise is resolved (unless the promise is rejected, in which case an error will be thrown that can be handled with normal JavaScript exception handling).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] If the parameter is not a promise, the parameter itself will be returned immediately.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Many libraries provide promise objects that can also be used with await, as long as they match the specification for native JavaScript promises.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] However, promises from the jQuery library were not Promises/A+ compatible until jQuery 3.0.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Node.js version 8 includes a utility that enables using the standard library callback-based methods as promises.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] The Future::AsyncAwait module was the subject of a Perl Foundation grant in September 2018.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Python 3.5 (2015) has added support for async/await as described in PEP 492 (written and implemented by Yury Selivanov).
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] On November 7, 2019, async/await was released on the stable version of Rust.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Async functions in Rust desugar to plain functions that return values that implement the Future trait.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Currently they are implemented with a finite-state machine.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Swift 5.5 (2021) added support for async/await as described in SE-0296.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] The async/await pattern is especially attractive to language designers of languages that do not have or control their own runtime, as async/await can be implemented solely as a transformation to a state machine in the compiler.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Supporters claim that asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written with async/await that looks almost like traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] In particular, it has been argued that await is the best way of writing asynchronous code in message-passing programs; in particular, being close to blocking code, readability and the minimal amount of boilerplate code were cited as await benefits.
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Critics of async/await note that the pattern tends to cause surrounding code to be asynchronous too; and that its contagious nature splits languages' library ecosystems between synchronous and asynchronous libraries and APIs, an issue often referred to as "function coloring".
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Alternatives to async/await that do not suffer from this issue are called "colorless".
[src:asyncio-python/async-await] Examples of colorless designs include Go's goroutines and Java's virtual threads.
[src:asyncio-python/asyncio] asyncio is a library to write **concurrent** code using the **async/await** syntax.
[src:asyncio-python/asyncio] asyncio is used as a foundation for multiple Python asynchronous frameworks that provide high-performance network and web-servers, database connection libraries, distributed task queues, etc.
[src:asyncio-python/asyncio] asyncio is often a perfect fit for IO-bound and high-level **structured** network code.
[src:asyncio-python/asyncio] Explanation of the fundamentals of asyncio.
[src:asyncio-python/asyncio] This module does not work or is not available on WebAssembly.
[src:asyncio-python/asyncio] See WebAssembly platforms for more information.
[src:asyncio-python/asyncio] This REPL provides limited compatibility with `PYTHON_BASIC_REPL`.
[src:asyncio-python/asyncio] It is recommended that the default REPL is used for full functionality and the latest features.
[src:asyncio-python/asyncio] Raises an auditing event `cpython.run_stdin` with no arguments.
[src:asyncio-python/asyncio] Changed in version 3.13: Uses PyREPL if possible, in which case `PYTHONSTARTUP` is also executed.
[src:asyncio-python/asyncio] The source code for asyncio can be found in Lib/asyncio/.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In computer programming, a **callback** is a programming pattern in which a function reference is passed from one context (consumer) to another (provider) such that the provider can call the function.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] If the function accesses state or functionality of the consumer, then the call is *back* to the consumer – backwards compared to the normal flow of control in which a consumer calls a provider.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] A function that accepts a callback parameter may be designed to call back before returning to its caller.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] But, more typically, a callback reference is stored by the provider so that it can call the function later (as *deferred*).
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] If the provider invokes the callback on the same thread as the consumer, then the call is *blocking*, a.k.a.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] If instead, the provider invokes the callback on a different thread, then the call is *non-blocking*, a.k.a.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be likened to leaving instructions with a tailor for what to do when a suit is ready, such as calling a specific phone number or delivering it to a given address.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] These instructions represent a callback: a function provided in advance to be executed later, often by a different part of the system and not necessarily by the one that received it.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] The difference between a general function reference and a callback can be subtle, and some use the terms interchangeably but distinction generally depends on programming intent.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] If the intent is like the telephone callback – that the original called party communicates back to the original caller – then it's a callback.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] A blocking callback runs in the execution context of the function that passes the callback.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] A deferred callback can run in a different context such as during interrupt or from a thread.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] As such, a deferred callback can be used for synchronization and delegating work to another thread.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be used for event handling.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Often, consuming code registers a callback for a particular type of event.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] When that event occurs, the callback is called.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Callbacks are often used to program the graphical user interface (GUI) of a program that runs in a windowing system.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] The application supplies a reference to a custom callback function for the windowing system to call.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] The windowing system calls this function to notify the application of events like mouse clicks and key presses.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be used to implement asynchronous processing.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] A caller requests an action and provides a callback to be called when the action completes which might be long after the request is made.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be used to implement polymorphism.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In the following pseudocode, `say_hi` can take either `write_status` or `write_error`.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] The callback technology is implemented differently by programming language.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In assembly, C, C++, Pascal, Modula-2 and other languages, a callback function is stored internally as a function pointer.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Using the same storage allows different languages to directly share callbacks without a design-time or runtime interoperability layer.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] For example, the Windows API is accessible via multiple languages, compilers and assemblers.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] C++ also allows objects to provide an implementation of the function call operation.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] The Standard Template Library accepts these objects (called *functors*) as parameters.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Many dynamic languages, such as JavaScript, Lua, Python, Perl and PHP, allow a function object to be passed.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] CLI languages such as C# and Visual Basic (.NET) (VB.NET) provide a type-safe encapsulating function reference known as delegate.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Events and event handlers, as used in .NET languages, provide for callbacks.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Functional programming languages generally support first-class functions, which can be passed as callbacks to other functions, stored as data or returned from functions.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Many languages, including Perl, Python, Ruby, Smalltalk, C++ (11+), C# and VB.NET (new versions) and most functional languages, support lambda expressions, unnamed functions with inline syntax, that generally act as callbacks.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In some languages, including Scheme, ML, JavaScript, Perl, Python, Smalltalk, PHP (since 5.3.0), C++ (11+), Java (since 8), and many others, a lambda can be a closure, i.e., can access variables locally defined in the context in which the lambda is defined.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In an object-oriented programming language such as Java versions before function-valued arguments, the behavior of a callback can be achieved by passing an object that implements an interface.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] The methods of this object are callbacks.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In PL/I and ALGOL 60, a callback procedure may need to be able to access local variables in containing blocks, so it is called through an *entry variable* containing both the entry point and context information.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Callbacks have a wide variety of uses, for example in error signaling: a Unix program might not want to terminate immediately when it receives SIGTERM, so to make sure that its termination is handled properly, it would register the cleanup function as a callback.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Another common use for callbacks in C is with C standard library functions used for sorting (`qsort()`) and searching (`lsearch()`, `bsearch()`) where a comparator function is passed as an argument to the routine to determine the collation order.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Callbacks may also be used to control whether a function acts or not: Xlib allows custom predicates to be specified to determine whether a program wishes to handle an event.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In the following C code, function `printNumber()` uses parameter `getNumber` as a blocking callback.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] `printNumber()` is called with `getAnswerToMostImportantQuestion()` which acts as a callback function.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In C++, functors can be used in addition to function pointer.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] A functor is an object with `operator()` defined.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] For example, the objects in `std::views` are functors.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In the following C# code, method `Helper.PerformAction` uses parameter `callback` as a blocking callback.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] `Helper.PerformAction` is called with `Log` which acts as a callback function.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] When run, the following is written to the console: "Callback was: Hello world".
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In the following JavaScript code, function `calculate` uses parameter `operate` as a blocking callback.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] `calculate` is called with `multiply` and then with `sum` which act as callback functions.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] The collection method `.each()` of the jQuery library uses the function passed to it as a blocking callback.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] It calls the callback for each item of the collection.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Deferred callbacks are commonly used for handling events from the user, the client and timers.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Examples can be found in `addEventListener`, Ajax and `XMLHttpRequest`.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In addition to using callbacks in JavaScript source code, C functions that take a function are supported via js-ctypes.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In the following Julia code, function `calculate` accepts a parameter `operate` that is used as a blocking callback.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] `calculate` is called with `square` which acts as a callback function.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] In the following Kotlin code, function `askAndAnswer` uses parameter `getAnswer` as a blocking callback.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] `askAndAnswer` is called with `getAnswerToMostImportantQuestion` which acts as a callback function.
[src:asyncio-python/callback-computer-programming] Running this will tell the user that the answer to their question is "42".
